Wow.  Things that look like expressions, but are most definitely not, through the magic of operator overloading.  So you can translate some expressions straightforwardly, but other expressions not, with the cases for what works and doesn't requiring careful thought.<p>So this works:<p><pre><code>    for_each(vp.begin(), vp.end(), cout << *_1 << '
');
</code></pre>
This doesn't:<p><pre><code>    for_each(vp.begin(), vp.end(), cout << '
' << *_1);
</code></pre>
But this does:<p><pre><code>    for_each(vp.begin(), vp.end(), cout << constant('
') << *_1);
</code></pre>
Considering how complex it is to figure out what works and what doesn't in that lambda slot, I'm not sure it's worth the effort.  Of course I'm not a C++ programmer, and this is yet another reason why that might not be such a bad thing.<p>(Note: this is regarding Boost lambda, if that wasn't clear.)
